{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.05,0,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64923"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7652"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA cell biology researcher observes the following features in a population of cultured cells:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECell shrinkage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENuclear fragmentation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChromatin condensation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFormation of membrane-bound vesicles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENo inflammatory response in surrounding tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EActivation of specific proteolytic enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cellular processes best explains these observations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apoptosis","Autophagy","Necrosis","Oncosis","Pyroptosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe features described are classic characteristics of \u003Cstrong\u003Eapoptosis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a programmed form of cell death. The hallmarks include cell shrinkage, nuclear fragmentation, chromatin condensation, and formation of membrane-bound vesicles (apoptotic bodies). Importantly, apoptosis does not trigger inflammation. Apoptosis occurs naturally during development (such as in digit formation), immune system regulation and removal of damaged cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by cell swelling, loss of membrane integrity, and inflammatory response, as seen in tissue damage from severe trauma or toxins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutophagy\u003C/strong\u003E is a self-degradative process involving double-membrane vesicles primarily for cellular recycling, which occurs during nutrient starvation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOncosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by cellular swelling, organelle swelling, and membrane rupture, commonly observed in myocardial ischaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyroptosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory programmed cell death involving cell lysis and release of inflammatory mediators, typically occurring during bacterial infections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe activation of specific proteolytic enzymes refers to caspases, which are essential mediators of apoptotic cell death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Apoptosis is characterised by cell shrinkage, chromatin condensation, and formation of membrane-bound vesicles.","Apoptosis is a programmed form of cell death that does not cause inflammation.","Caspase enzymes are key mediators of apoptotic cell death."],"references":["Alberts B, Bray D, Johnson A, Lewis J, Raff M, Roberts K, et al. Cell communities: tissues, stem cells, and cancer. Essential cell biology, 4th New York Edition: Garland Science; 2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64923"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64923"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T11:17:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T11:17:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7508"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d